Let us think back of the previous lessons,
and see what we have learned so far.
We learned about the use of tempo,
so we know when it is good to have tempo and how to make it useful
we also learned the style of developments
one was positional style, another was straight style
we learned that whatever style we use, the support of inner stones is very important
and we learned that when we develop, then the diagonal lines are good.
Is all that easy for you?
positional style is difficult to grasp still
keep tempo,positional and straight style,inner structions,and diag.
Today we will talk about "Use of Lines".
This is perhaps the part of the tactics that we meet frequently in our game.
Both beginners and experts know how to make lines.
You just find the spots on board that gives you as many useful lines as possible, and likely that is a good move.
There is no problem about that.
You all can do it easily.
Once we have some lines, then how to use them and when.
This is what we will study today.
These moves are all famous and logical as well.
Lets forget the theory that we know,
and analyse it as if we see it for the first time.
The first thing we see is
Whenever we have a line, there is a question - use it or not.
And being good ad such decisions,
makes the difference between master and beginner.
Of course, we start with basic examples,
and slowly approach to the more complex ones.
Lets first talk about using the three.
When should we use a three. There are some reasons:
1. we are beginning the winning attack
2. we use the three to extend the space power for us
if we simply go here, we give up the valuable j10 point
so we use the three to grab more space for black's base

1. we are beginning the winning attack
2. we use the three to extend the space power for us
3. we use the three in defense purpose, because thats our only choice
Any three that does not match with one of the 3 choices here, is a BAD three.

Never use the four unless you have to!
There are 3 reasons you may have to use a four:
1. make your VCF
2. to prevent opponent from taking this point
3. the only defense.
if your four does not meet any of these conditions then it is a BAD four
Is it a good four or bad?
no VCF, not important pt, not only defence
we dont make ANY four unless we have to. And this time we DONT have to, because none of the 3 rules forces us
which means, white did not need to use four too early
and by saving a four for later use we have many benefits:
2. we didn not give opponent additional stone
3. we can use our four anytime late for attack or defense purposes
4. a not played four can later be used in two ways, not just one
we gave up the choice to use it e6 later
but now we have at least two choices
which means we have more freedom
So, just remember always, do not use a four unless you have to.
